{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","parts":[{"id":"prt_d774de20b0012bQuH29hhK4Imf","messageID":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","sessionID":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_f23d665b1757479e881e955f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: \n2: |Build Status| |Code Coverage| |Commit Activity| |Good First Issues|\n3: \n4: #################\n5: ARMI Introduction\n6: #################\n7: \n8: The Advanced Reactor Modeling Interface (ARMI\\ :sup:`®`) is an open-source tool that streamlines your nuclear reactor\n9: design/analysis needs by providing a software *reactor at your fingertips* and a rich ecosystem of utilities working in\n10: concert. It is made for and by professional reactor analysis teams and is maintained by\n11: `TerraPower LLC <http://terrapower.com/>`_, a nuclear technology development company.\n12: \n13: ARMI:\n14: \n15: * Provides a hub-and-spoke mechanism to standardize communication and coupling between physics kernels and the\n16:   specialist analysts who use them,\n17: \n18: * Facilitates the creation and execution of detailed models and complex analysis methodologies,\n19: \n20: * Provides an ecosystem within which to rapidly and collaboratively build new analysis and physics simulation\n21:   capabilities, and\n22: \n23: * Provides useful utilities to assist in reactor development.\n24: \n25: A few demos of ARMI can be seen in the `ARMI example gallery <https://terrapower.github.io/armi/gallery/index.html>`_.\n26: \n27: Using ARMI plus a collection of ARMI-aware physics plugins, an engineering team can perform a full analysis of a reactor\n28: system and then repeat the same level of analysis with some changed input parameters for almost no additional cost. Even\n29: better, thousands of perturbed cases can be executed in parallel on large clusters, helping conceptual design teams home\n30: in on an optimal design. Or design teams can analyze sensitivities all the way from, for example, an impurity in a\n31: control material to the peak structural temperature in a design-basis transient.\n32: \n33: .. note:: ARMI does not come with a full selection of physics kernels. They will need to be acquired or developed for\n34:    your specific project in order to make full use of this tool. Many of the example use-cases discussed in this manual\n35:    require functionality that is not included in the open-source ARMI Framework.\n36: \n37: In general, ARMI aims to enhance the quality, ease, and rigor of computational nuclear reactor design and analysis.\n38: Additional high-level overview about this system can be found in [#touranarmi]_.\n39: \n40: \n41: .. list-table:: Quick links\n42:    :widths: 30 70\n43: \n44:    * - Source code\n45:      - https://github.com/terrapower/armi\n46:    * - Documentation\n47:      - https://terrapower.github.io/armi\n48:    * - First time contributor's guide\n49:      - https://terrapower.github.io/armi/developer/first_time_contributors.html\n50:    * - Bug tracker\n51:      - https://github.com/terrapower/armi/issues\n52:    * - Plugin directory\n53:      - https://github.com/terrapower/armi-plugin-directory\n54:    * - Contact\n55:      - armi-devs@terrapower.com\n56: \n57: Quick start\n58: ***********\n59: Before starting, you need to have `Python <https://www.python.org/downloads/>`_ 3.9+.\n60: \n61: Get the ARMI code, install the prerequisites, and fire up the launcher with the following commands. You probably want to\n62: do this in a virtual environment as described in the\n63: `Installation documentation <https://terrapower.github.io/armi/installation.html>`_. Otherwise, the dependencies could\n64: conflict with your system dependencies.\n65: \n66: First, upgrade your version of pip::\n67: \n68:     $ pip install -U pip>=22.1\n69: \n70: Now clone and install ARMI::\n71: \n72:     $ git clone https://github.com/terrapower/armi\n73:     $ cd armi\n74:     $ pip install -e .\n75:     $ armi --help\n76: \n77: The ARMI tests are meant to be run using `pytest <https://docs.pytest.org/en/8.0.x/>`_ locally::\n78: \n79:     $ pip install -e \".[test]\"\n80:     $ pytest -n 4 armi\n81: \n82: From here, we recommend going through a few of our\n83: `gallery examples <https://terrapower.github.io/armi/gallery/index.html>`_ and\n84: `tutorials <https://terrapower.github.io/armi/tutorials/index.html>`_ to start touring the features and capabilities and\n85: then move on to the `User Manual <https://terrapower.github.io/armi/user/index.html>`_.\n86: \n87: \n88: Background\n89: **********\n90: Nuclear reactor design requires, among other things, answers to the following questions:\n91: \n92: * Where are the neutrons? How fast are they moving? In which direction?\n93: \n94: * How quickly are atomic nuclei splitting? How long until the fuel runs out? How many atoms in the structure are being\n95:   energetically displaced?\n96: \n97: * How much heat do these reactions produce? How quickly must coolant flow past the fuel to maintain appropriate\n98:   temperatures? What are the temperatures of the fuel, coolant, and structure?\n99: \n100: * Can the structural arrangement support itself given the temperatures and pressures induced by the flowing coolant? For\n101:   how long?\n102: \n103: * If a pump loses power or a control rod accidentally withdraws, how quickly will the chain reaction stop while keeping\n104:   radiation contained?\n105: \n106: * How much used nuclear fuel is generated per useful energy produced? How long until it decays to stability?\n107: \n108: * Where and when should we move the fuel to most economically maintain the chain reaction?\n109: \n110: * What's the dose and activation above the head and in the secondary loop?\n111: \n112: * How does containment handle various postulated accidents?\n113: \n114: * How does the building handle earthquakes?\n115: \n116: Digital computers have assisted in nuclear technology development since the days of the ENIAC in the 1940s. We now\n117: understand reactor physics well enough to build detailed simulations, which can answer many of these design questions in\n118: a cost-effective, and flexible manner. This allows us to simulate all kinds of different reactors with different fuels,\n119: coolants, moderators, power levels, safety systems, and power cycles. We can run our virtual reactors through the\n120: decades, tossing various off-normal conditions at them now and then, to see how they perform in terms of capability,\n121: economics, and safety.\n122: \n123: Perhaps surprisingly, some nuclear software written in the 1960s is still in use today. These codes are validated\n124: against physical experiments that no longer exist. Meanwhile, new cutting-edge nuclear software is being developed for\n125: todays powerful computers. Both old and new, these tools are often challenging to operate and coordinate to produce a\n126: full reactor analysis.\n127: \n128: The ARMI approach was born out of this situation: how can we best leverage an eclectic mix of legacy and modern tools\n129: with a small team to do full-scope analysis? We built a framework that lets us automate the tedious, uncoupled, and\n130: error-prone parts of reactor engineering/analysis work. We can turn around a very meaningful and detailed core analysis\n131: given a major change (e.g. change power by 50%) in just a few weeks. We can dispatch hundreds of parameter sweeps to\n132: multiple machines and then perform multi-objective optimization on the resulting design space.\n133: \n134: The ARMI system is largely written in the Python programming language. Its high-level nature allows nuclear and\n135: mechanical engineers to rapidly automate their analysis tasks from their sub-specialties. This helps eliminate the\n136: translation step between computer-scientists and power plant design engineers. This allows good division of labor: the\n137: computer scientists can focus on the overall performance and maintainability of the framework, while the power plant\n138: engineers focus on power plant engineering.\n139: \n140: We have spent over 10 years developing this system. Because of ARMI's high-level nature, we believe we can collaborate\n141: effectively with all ongoing reactor software developments.\n142: \n143: Communication and coupling\n144: **************************\n145: ARMI provides a central place for all physics kernels to interact: the Reactor Model. All modules read *state*\n146: information from this Reactor and write their output to it. This common interface allows seamless communication and\n147: coupling between different physics sub-specialties. If you plug one new physics kernel into ARMI, it becomes coupled to\n148: N other kernels. The ARMI Framework, depicted in green below, is the majority of the open source package. Several\n149: skeletal analysis routines are included as well to perform basic data management and to help align efforts on external\n150: physics kernels.\n151: \n152: .. figure:: https://terrapower.github.io/armi/_static/armiSchematicView.png\n153:    :figclass: align-center\n154: \n155:    **Figure 1.** The schematic representation of the ARMI data model.\n156: \n157: \n158: Automation\n159: **********\n160: ARMI can quickly and easily produce complex input files with high levels of detail in various approximations. This\n161: enables users to perform rapid high-fidelity analyses to make sure all important physics are captured. It also enables\n162: sensitivity studies of different modeling approximations (e.g. symmetries, transport vs. diffusion vs. Monte Carlo,\n163: subchannel vs. CFD, etc.).\n164: \n165: \n166: .. figure:: https://terrapower.github.io/armi/_static/armiGeometries.png\n167:    :figclass: align-center\n168: \n169:    **Figure 2.** A variety of approximations in hexagonal geometry (1/3-core, full core, pin detailed, etc.) are shown,\n170:    all derived from one consistent input file. ARMI supports Cartesian, Hex, RZ, and RZTheta geometric grids and\n171:    includes many geometric components. Additionally, users can provide custom geometric elements.\n172: \n173: \n174: New analysis and physics capabilities\n175: *************************************\n176: The ARMI reactor model is fully accessible via a Python-based API, meaning that power-users and developers have full\n177: access to the details of the plant at all times. Developers adding new physics features can take advantage of the ARMI\n178: data management structure by simply reading and writing to the Reactor state. Leveraging the infrastructure of ARMI,\n179: progress can be made rapidly.\n180: \n181: Power-user analysts can modify the plant in many ways. For instance, removing all sodium coolant is a one-liner::\n182: \n183:     core.setNumberDensity('NA23',0.0)\n184: \n185: and finding the peak power density is easy::\n186: \n187:     core.getMaxParam('pdens')\n188: \n189: Any ARMI state can be written out to whichever format the user desires, meaning that nominally identical cases can be\n190: produced for multiple similar codes in sensitivity studies. To read power densities, simply read them off the assembly\n191: objects. Instead of producing spreadsheets and making plots manually, analysts may write scripts to generate output\n192: reports that run automatically.\n193: \n194: Writing a module within ARMI automatically features access to the ARMI API, including:\n195: \n196: * Cross section processing\n197: * Material properties\n198: * Thermal expansion\n199: * Database persistence\n200: * Data visualization\n201: * A code testing, documentation, and version control system\n202: \n203: \n204: Use cases\n205: *********\n206: Given an input describing a reactor, a typical ARMI run loops over a set of plugins in a certain sequence. Some plugins\n207: trigger third-party simulation codes, producing input files for them, executing them, and translating the output back\n208: onto the reactor model. Other plugins perform physics simulations directly.\n209: \n210: For example, one ARMI sequence may involve the calculation of:\n211: \n212: * nuclear cross sections\n213: * global flux and power\n214: * subchannel temperatures\n215: * duct wall pressures\n216: * cladding strain and wastage\n217: * fission gas pressure\n218: * reactivity feedbacks\n219: * flow orificing\n220: * the equilibrium fuel cycle\n221: * control rod worth\n222: * shutdown margin\n223: * frequency stability margins\n224: * peak cladding temperature\n225: * transient analysis\n226: * total levelized cost of electricity for the run\n227: \n228: Another ARMI sequence may simply compute the cost of feed uranium and enrichment in an initial core and quit.\n229: \n230: Larger siumulations may also run through the multi-objective design optimization system, which runs many cases with\n231: input perturbations to help find the best overall system, considering all important physics at the same time.\n232: \n233: Other interest may come from the following:\n234: \n235: The Research Scientist\n236: ======================\n237: A nuclear reactor research scientist, at a national lab or university, may benefit from ARMI. An ARMI workflow can\n238: reduce the time spent on data management. ARMI can handle the tedium so that researchers can better focus on designing\n239: and testing their research.\n240: \n241: For example, if an ARMI input file describing the FFTF reactor is provided, the researcher can start running benchmark\n242: cases with their new code method very rapidly, rather than spending the time building their own FFTF model.\n243: \n244: If someone wants to try varying nuclear cross sections by a percent here and there to compute sensitivities, ARMI is a\n245: perfect platform upon which to operate.\n246: \n247: If a reactor designer wants to try out a new Machine Learning algorithm for fuel management, plugging it into ARMI and\n248: having it run on all the physics kernels of the ARMI ecosystem will be a great way to prove its true value (note that\n249: this requires a rich ARMI physics ecosystem).\n250: \n251: The Nuclear Startup Engineer\n252: ============================\n253: As various companies evaluate their ideas, they need tools for analysis. They can pick up ARMI and save 10 years of\n254: development and hit the ground running by plugging in their design-specific physics kernels and proprietary design\n255: inputs. ARMI's parameter sweep features, reactor model, and parallel utilities will all come in handy immediately.\n256: \n257: \n258: Operating and Vendor Engineers\n259: ==============================\n260: People at well-established utilities or vendors can hook ARMI into their legacy systems and increase their overall\n261: productivity.\n262: \n263: The Enthusiast\n264: ==============\n265: If an enthusiast wants to try out a reactor idea they have, they can use ARMI (plus some physics kernels) to quickly get\n266: some performance metrics. They can see if their idea has wings, and if it does, they can then find a way to bring it to\n267: engineering and commercial reality.\n268: \n269: \n270: History of ARMI\n271: ***************\n272: ARMI was originally created by TerraPower, LLC near Seattle WA starting in 2009. Its founding mission was to determine\n273: the optimal fuel management operations required to transition a fresh Traveling Wave Reactor core from startup into an\n274: equilibrium state. It started out automating the Argonne National Lab (ANL) fast reactor neutronics codes, MC2 and\n275: REBUS. The reactor model design was made with the intention of adding other physics capabilities later. Soon, simple\n276: thermal hydraulics were added and it's grown ever since. It has continuously evolved towards a general reactor analysis\n277: framework.\n278: \n279: Following requests by outside parties to use ARMI, we started working on a more modular architecture for ARMI, allowing\n280: some of the intertwined physics capabilities to be separated out as plugins from the standalone framework.\n281: \n282: The nuclear industry is small, and it faces many challenges. It also has a tradition of secrecy. As a result, there is\n283: risk of overlapping work being done by other entities.\n284: \n285: We hypothesize that collaborating on software systems can help align some efforts worldwide, increasing quality and\n286: efficiency. In reactor development, the idea is generally cheap. It's the shakedown, technology and supply chain\n287: development, engineering demo, and commercial demo that are the hard parts.\n288: \n289: Thus, ARMI was released under an open-source license in 2019 to facilitate mutually beneficial collaboration across the\n290: nuclear industry, where many teams are independently developing similar reactor analysis/automation frameworks.\n291: \n292: We also hope that if more people can rapidly analyze the performance of their reactor ideas, limited available funding\n293: can be spent more effectively.\n294: \n295: \n296: System Requirements\n297: *******************\n298: Being largely written in the Python programming language, the ARMI system works on most platforms.  It can perform\n299: meaningful analysis on a single laptop, but the full value of design optimization and large problems is realized with\n300: parallel runs over large clusters (using the optional ``mpi4py`` library).\n301: \n302: .. _getting-help:\n303: \n304: Getting Help\n305: ************\n306: You can get help with ARMI by either making issues on our `github page <https://github.com/terrapower/armi/issues>`_ or\n307: by e-mailing armi-devs@terrapower.com.\n308: \n309: Disclaimers\n310: ***********\n311: Due to TerraPower goals and priorities, many ARMI modules were developed with the sodium-cooled fast reactors as a\n312: target, and are not necessarily yet optimized for other plants. This is a known issue with code organization and we are\n313: working on it. On the other hand, the framework is sufficiently general that people have modeled other reactor types\n314: with ARMI, including thermal reactors.\n315: \n316: ARMI was developed within a rapidly changing R&D environment. It evolved accordingly, and naturally carries some legacy.\n317: We continuously attempt to identify and update problematic parts of the code. Users should understand that ARMI is not a\n318: polished consumer software product, but rather a powerful and flexible engineering tool. It has the potential to\n319: accelerate work on many kinds of reactors.\n320: \n321: ARMI has been written to support specific engineering/design tasks. As such, polish in the GUIs and output is somewhat\n322: lacking.\n323: \n324: The ARMI framework uses the ``camelCase`` style, which is not the standard style for Python. As this is an issue of\n325: style, it is not considered worth the API-breaking cost to our downstream users to change it.\n326: \n327: \n328: License\n329: *******\n330: TerraPower and ARMI are registered trademarks of TerraPower, LLC. Other trademarks and registered trademarks used in\n331: this Manual are the property of the respective trademark holders.\n332: \n333: The ARMI system is licensed as follows:\n334: \n335: .. code-block:: none\n336: \n337: \tCopyright 2009 TerraPower, LLC\n338: \n339: \tLicensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n340: \tyou may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n341: \tYou may obtain a copy of the License at\n342: \n343: \t    http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n344: \n345: \tUnless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n346: \tdistributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n347: \tWITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n348: \tSee the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n349: \tlimitations under the License.\n350: \n351: Be careful when including any dependency in ARMI (say in the ``pyproject.toml`` file) not to include anything with a\n352: license that supersedes our Apache license. For instance, any third-party Python library included in ARMI with a GPL\n353: license will make the whole project fall under the GPL license. But a lot of potential users of ARMI will want to keep\n354: some of their work private, so we can't allow any GPL dependencies.\n355: \n356: For that reason, it is generally considered best-practice in the ARMI ecosystem to only use third-party Python libraries\n357: that have MIT or BSD licenses.\n358: \n359: .. [#touranarmi] Touran, Nicholas W., et al. \"Computational tools for the integrated design of advanced nuclear reactors.\"\n360:    Engineering 3.4 (2017): 518-526. https://doi.org/10.1016/J.ENG.2017.04.016\n361: \n362: .. |Build Status| image:: https://github.com/terrapower/armi/actions/workflows/unittests.yaml/badge.svg?branch=main\n363:     :target: https://github.com/terrapower/armi/actions/workflows/unittests.yaml\n364: \n365: .. |Code Coverage| image:: https://codecov.io/gh/terrapower/armi/branch/main/graph/badge.svg\n366:     :target: https://app.codecov.io/gh/terrapower/armi/tree/main\n367: \n368: .. |Commit Activity| image:: https://img.shields.io/github/commit-activity/m/terrapower/armi\n369:     :target: https://github.com/terrapower/armi/pulse\n370: \n371: .. |Good First Issues| image:: https://img.shields.io/github/issues/terrapower/armi/good%20first%20issue\n372:     :target: https://github.com/terrapower/armi/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22good+first+issue%22\n\n(End of file - total 372 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n|Build Status| |Code Coverage| |Commit Activity| |Good First Issues|\n\n#################\nARMI Introduction\n#################\n\nThe Advanced Reactor Modeling Interface (ARMI\\ :sup:`®`) is an open-source tool that streamlines your nuclear reactor\ndesign/analysis needs by providing a software *reactor at your fingertips* and a rich ecosystem of utilities working in\nconcert. It is made for and by professional reactor analysis teams and is maintained by\n`TerraPower LLC <http://terrapower.com/>`_, a nuclear technology development company.\n\nARMI:\n\n* Provides a hub-and-spoke mechanism to standardize communication and coupling between physics kernels and the\n  specialist analysts who use them,\n\n* Facilitates the creation and execution of detailed models and complex analysis methodologies,\n\n* Provides an ecosystem within which to rapidly and collaboratively build new analysis and physics simulation","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.rst","time":{"start":1775823086361,"end":1775823086373}}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","parts":[{"id":"prt_d774de3a7001rSxMdNNSv88cUw","messageID":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","sessionID":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_425346295957475da5955917","state":{"status":"pending","input":{},"raw":""}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","parts":[{"id":"prt_d774de3a7001rSxMdNNSv88cUw","messageID":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","sessionID":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_425346295957475da5955917","state":{"status":"running","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/pyproject.toml"},"time":{"start":1775823086931}}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","parts":[{"id":"prt_d774de3a7001rSxMdNNSv88cUw","messageID":"msg_d774dda05001WG6qY0Ll48o1ZE","sessionID":"ses_288b23549ffeOcHU4Vmxxc6Hjq","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_425346295957475da5955917","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/pyproject.toml"},"output":"<path>/workspace/pyproject.toml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Copyright 2023 TerraPower, LLC\n2: #\n3: # Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n4: # you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n5: # You may obtain a copy of the License at\n6: #\n7: #     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n8: #\n9: # Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n10: # distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n11: # WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n12: # See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n13: # limitations under the License.\n14: \n15: #######################################################################\n16: #                        GENERAL PYTHON CONFIG                        #\n17: #######################################################################\n18: [build-system]\n19: requires = [\"setuptools>=61.2\"]\n20: build-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\"\n21: \n22: [project]\n23: name = \"armi\"\n24: version = \"0.7.0\"\n25: description = \"An open-source nuclear reactor analysis automation framework that helps design teams increase efficiency and quality.\"\n26: license-files = [\"LICENSE.md\", \"AUTHORS\"]\n27: requires-python = \">3.8\"\n28: readme = \"README.rst\"\n29: authors = [\n30:     { name=\"TerraPower, LLC\", email=\"armi-devs@terrapower.com\" },\n31: ]\n32: dependencies = [\n33:     \"coverage>=7.2.0\", # Code coverage tool. Sadly baked into every Case.\n34:     \"h5py>=3.0,<=3.9 ; python_version < '3.11.0'\",\n35:     \"h5py>=3.9 ; python_version >= '3.11.0'\", # Needed because our database files are H5 format\n36:     \"matplotlib>=3.5.3,<3.8.0 ; python_version < '3.11.0'\",\n37:     \"matplotlib>=3.5.3 ; python_version >= '3.11.0'\", # Important plotting library\n38:     \"numpy>=1.21\", # Important math library\n39:     \"ordered-set>=3.1.1\", # A useful data structure\n40:     \"pluggy>=1.2.0\", # Central tool behind the ARMI Plugin system\n41:     \"pyevtk>=1.2.0\", # Handles binary VTK visualization files\n42:     \"ruamel.yaml>=0.19.1 ; python_version >= '3.11.0'\", # Our foundational YAML library\n43:     \"ruamel.yaml<=0.17.21 ; python_version < '3.11.0'\", # Our foundational YAML library\n44:     \"scipy>=1.7.0\", # Used for curve-fitting and matrix math\n45:     \"sympy>=1.14\", # Used to represent mathematical curves for material properties\n46:     \"toml>0.9.5\", # Needed to parse the pyproject.toml file\n47:     \"voluptuous>=0.12.1\", # Used to validate YAML data files\n48:     \"yamlize==0.7.1\", # Custom YAML-to-object library\n49: ]\n50: classifiers = [\n51:     \"Development Status :: 4 - Beta\",\n52:     \"Intended Audience :: Science/Research\",\n53:     \"License :: OSI Approved :: Apache Software License\",\n54:     \"Operating System :: OS Independent\",\n55:     \"Programming Language :: Python\",\n56:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3\",\n57:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3 :: Only\",\n58:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.9\",\n59:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.10\",\n60:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.11\",\n61:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.12\",\n62:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13\",\n63:     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.14\",\n64:     \"Topic :: Scientific/Engineering :: Information Analysis\",\n65: ]\n66: \n67: [project.urls]\n68: Homepage = \"https://terrapower.github.io/armi/\"\n69: Documentation = \"https://terrapower.github.io/armi\"\n70: Changelog = \"https://github.com/terrapower/armi/releases\"\n71: Repository = \"https://github.com/terrapower/armi\"\n72: \"Bug Tracker\" = \"https://github.com/terrapower/armi/issues\"\n73: \n74: [project.optional-dependencies]\n75: grids = [\"wxpython==4.2.1\"]\n76: memprof = [\"psutil\"]\n77: mpi = [\"mpi4py\"]\n78: test = [\n79:     \"ipykernel>=6.0.0\", # IPython Kernel (We run test notebooks from the doc tutorials.)\n80:     \"jupyter_client>=7.0.0\", # Reference implementation of the Jupyter protocol\n81:     \"nbconvert>=7.0.0\", # Converting Jupyter Notebooks to other formats\n82:     \"nbformat>=5.5.0\", # Jupyter Notebook reader\n83:     \"pytest-cov>=4.0.0\", # coverage plugin\n84:     \"pytest-xdist>=3.0.0\", # To spread our tests over multiple CPUs\n85:     \"pytest>=7.0.0\", # Our primary test tooling\n86:     \"ruff==0.9.7\", # Linting and code formatting (version-pinned)\n87: ]\n88: docs = [\n89: ######################################################################################\n90: # These are most specified that usual, because Sphinx docs seem to be quite fragile. #\n91: #                                                                                    #\n92: # Officially, we build our docs with Python 3.13.                                    #\n93: ######################################################################################\n94:     \"docutils==0.21.2\", # Needed by sphinx-rtd-them\n95:     \"ipykernel>=6.0.0\", # iPython kernel to run Jupyter notebooks\n96:     \"Jinja2==3.1.5\", # Used in numpydoc and nbconvert\n97:     \"nbsphinx-link==1.3.1\", # Adds Jupyter NBs to Sphinx source root\n98:     \"nbsphinx==0.9.6\", # Parses Jupyter notebooks\n99:     \"pandoc\", # Must be in the path (to convert file formats)\n100:     \"pylint\", # Generates UML diagrams\n101:     \"pypdf==5.3.1\", # Generating a single PDF file for the Sphinx documentation\n102:     \"setuptools\",  # needed for conf.py tooling\n103:     \"sphinx-data-viewer==0.1.5\",\n104:     \"sphinx-gallery==0.13.0\", # Builds an HTML version of a Python script and puts it into a gallery\n105:     \"sphinx-needs==4.2.0\", # Requirements traceability matrices for QA\n106:     \"sphinx-rtd-theme==3.0.2\", # Read-The-Docs theme for Sphinx\n107:     \"sphinx-test-reports==1.1.0\", # sphinx-needs test reports in the STR\n108:     \"Sphinx==7.4.7\", # central library used to build our docs\n109:     \"sphinxcontrib-apidoc==0.5.0\", # More easily document our API\n110:     \"sphinxcontrib-applehelp==2.0.0\",\n111:     \"sphinxcontrib-devhelp==2.0.0\",\n112:     \"sphinxcontrib-htmlhelp==2.1.0\",\n113:     \"sphinxcontrib-jquery==4.1\", # Handle missing jquery errors\n114:     \"sphinxcontrib-jsmath==1.0.1\",\n115:     \"sphinxcontrib-plantuml==0.30\", # UML support in sphinx-needs\n116:     \"sphinxcontrib-qthelp==2.0.0\",\n117:     \"sphinxcontrib-serializinghtml==2.0.0\",\n118:     \"sphinxext-opengraph==0.9.1\", # Generates OpenGraph metadata to make cards for social media\n119:     \"unittest-xml-reporting==3.2.0\", # Allows us to generate junit XML test reports\n120: ]\n121: \n122: [project.scripts]\n123: armi = \"armi.__main__:main\"\n124: \n125: [tool.setuptools.packages]\n126: find = {}\n127: \n128: \n129: #######################################################################\n130: #                             RUFF CONFIG                             #\n131: #######################################################################\n132: [tool.ruff]\n133: # This is the exact version of Ruff we use.\n134: required-version = \"0.9.7\"\n135: \n136: # Assume Python 3.13\n137: target-version = \"py313\"\n138: \n139: # Setting line-length to 120\n140: line-length = 120\n141: \n142: # Exclude a variety of commonly ignored directories.\n143: exclude = [\n144:     \".bzr\",\n145:     \".direnv\",\n146:     \".eggs\",\n147:     \".git\",\n148:     \".git-rewrite\",\n149:     \".hg\",\n150:     \".mypy_cache\",\n151:     \".nox\",\n152:     \".pants.d\",\n153:     \".pytype\",\n154:     \".ruff_cache\",\n155:     \".svn\",\n156:     \".tox\",\n157:     \".venv\",\n158:     \"__pycache__\",\n159:     \"__pypackages__\",\n160:     \"_build\",\n161:     \"buck-out\",\n162:     \"build\",\n163:     \"dist\",\n164:     \"doc/tutorials/armi-example-app\",\n165:     \"node_modules\",\n166:     \"venv\",\n167: ]\n168: \n169: [tool.ruff.lint]\n170: # Enable pycodestyle (E) and Pyflakes (F) codes by default.\n171: # D - NumPy docstring rules\n172: # I - Sorting imports\n173: # N801 - Class name should use CapWords convention\n174: # SIM - code simplification rules\n175: # TID - tidy imports\n176: select = [\"D\", \"E\", \"F\", \"I\", \"N801\", \"SIM\", \"TID\"]\n177: \n178: # Ruff rules we ignore (for now) because they are not 100% automatable\n179: #\n180: # D100 - Missing docstring in public module\n181: # D101 - Missing docstring in public class\n182: # D102 - Missing docstring in public method\n183: # D103 - Missing docstring in public function\n184: # D106 - Missing docstring in public nested class\n185: # D401 - First line of docstring should be in imperative mood\n186: # D404 - First word of the docstring should not be \"This\"\n187: # SIM102 - Use a single if statement instead of nested if statements\n188: # SIM105 - Use contextlib.suppress({exception}) instead of try-except-pass\n189: # SIM108 - Use ternary operator {contents} instead of if-else-block\n190: # SIM114 - Combine if branches using logical or operator\n191: # SIM115 - Use context handler for opening files\n192: # SIM117 - Use a single with statement with multiple contexts instead of nested with statements\n193: \n194: # Ruff rules we ignore because we don't want them\n195: #\n196: # D105 - we don't need to document well-known magic methods\n197: # D205 - 1 blank line required between summary line and description\n198: # E731 - we can use lambdas however we want\n199: # RUF100 - no unused noqa stat